04103nam a22005775i 9780226514642DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20082005ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265146427 a10.7208/97802265146422doi  a(DE-B1597)523713  a(OCoLC)781253715  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aP117.M359 2005 7aPSY0000002bisacsh04a153.69a808.51 aMcNeill, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGesture and Thought /cDavid McNeill. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b92 figures, 13 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart 1. Preliminaries -- tPart 2. Dialectic -- tPart 3. Brain and Origins -- tAppendix. Methods of Gesture Recording and Transcription, Including New Semi-Automated Methods, Plus ‘The Growth Point’—a Poem -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGesturing is such an integral yet unconscious part of communication that we are mostly oblivious to it. But if you observe anyone in conversation, you are likely to see his or her fingers, hands, and arms in some form of spontaneous motion. Why? David McNeill, a pioneer in the ongoing study of the relationship between gesture and language, set about answering this question over twenty-five years ago. In Gesture and Thought he brings together years of this research, arguing that gesturing, an act which has been popularly understood as an accessory to speech, is actually a dialectical component of language. Gesture and Thought expands on McNeill’s acclaimed classic Hand and Mind. While that earlier work demonstrated what gestures reveal about thought, here gestures are shown to be active participants in both speaking and thinking. Expanding on an approach introduced by Lev Vygotsky in the 1930s, McNeill posits that gestures are key ingredients in an “imagery-language dialectic” that fuels both speech and thought. Gestures are both the “imagery” and components of “language.” The smallest element of this dialectic is the “growth point,” a snapshot of an utterance at its beginning psychological stage. Utilizing several innovative experiments he created and administered with subjects spanning several different age, gender, and language groups, McNeill shows how growth points organize themselves into utterances and extend to discourse at the moment of speaking. An ambitious project in the ongoing study of the relationship of human communication and thought, Gesture and Thought is a work of such consequence that it will influence all subsequent theory on the subject.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGesture. 0aLanguage and languages. 0aLiterature. 0aPsycholinguistics. 0aPsychology. 0aSign language. 0aSpeech. 0aThought and thinking. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226514642423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226514642.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles